 /> Having the ghetto opened allowed for smuggling of food in by nearby Aryan community. After it was closed, this responsibility fell on the [[Jewish Ghetto Police|Jewish Police]]. This section of Jewish Police was led by Diestler, an ex soldier of the Austrian army.<ref name=\":2\" /> Trades between the Jewish residents and the Jewish Police occurred at night.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Jewish people living in the ghetto were also low on winter apparel and supplies because the German Troops took them to support the [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of Russia]]. In June 1941, 180 Jews were shot in the streets and 560 Jews sent to the [[Belzec extermination camp]].<ref name=\":6\" />  \n\nIn mid-July 1942, the open ghetto became a closed ghetto surrounded by a fence.<ref name=\":2\" /> <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Vashem|first=Yad|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&hl=fr&id=MFn3KeENnA0C&q=brzesko#v=snippet&q=brzesko&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Jewish Life Before and During the Holocaust: A-J|date=2001|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-9376-3|language=en}}</ref> It spread across 3 areas: Berka Joselewicza Street, then all the buildings north of the Market Square up to the Rynek Sienny (known today as Sobieskiego Street and [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin|Chopin]] Street), and finally G\u0142owackiego Street up to Trzcianka and the Kazimierz Wielki Square.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://sztetl.org.pl/pl/miejscowosci/b/463-brzesko/116-miejsca-martyrologii/44948-getto-w-brzesku|title=Getto w Brzesku {{!}} Wirtualny Sztetl|website=sztetl.org.pl|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Initially 3,000 Jews lived there. However, 6,000 Jews had to live in this small part of the town by summer 1942. Overpopulation became a problem when the ghetto was fenced off. The camp had about ten people per window which decreased sanitation throughout the camp. This led to an outbreak of typhoid. [[Typhoid fever|Typhoid]] was one of the major causes of death within the ghetto along with starvation.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> One of the doctors helping those with Typhoid fever was Maurycy Gross.<ref name=\":2\" /> Even with the outbreak of typhoid. the main source of death within the ghetto was the German forces. When a Jew was shot by someone in the Nazi party, they would force other Jews within the community to sign a document stating they died from natural causes. In addition, the Jews had to pay for any ammunition used to shoot other Jewish people within Brzesko. During the year of 1942, three [[Aktion T4|Aktions]] took place within the Brzesko Ghetto and were conducted by the Order Police which included people such as Lapsch, Wagner, and Mikler. On 18 June 1942, 180 Jews were killed in the streets and 560 deported to the [[Belzec extermination camp]] for the third Aktion.<ref name=\":6\" /> In December 1942, fifteen Jews were brought from [[Zakliczyn]] and shot at the cemetery.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\n== Deportation to extermination camps ==\nOn 17 September 1942 (or on the 12th<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|last=Vashem|first=Yad|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&hl=fr&id=MFn3KeENnA0C&q=brzesko#v=snippet&q=brzesko&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Jewish Life Before and During the Holocaust: A-J|date=2001|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-9376-3|language=en}}</ref>), the nazis liquidate the ghetto.<ref name=\":2\" />\u00a0About 2,000 Jewish people are sent to the [[Belzec extermination camp]], about 150 miles from Brzesko. Another 4,000 Jewish people were sent to the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz death camp]] that same year.<ref name=\":1\" /> In order to accomplish the deportation, all the Jews living in Brzesko were gathered in the square of the town.<ref name=\":0\" /> Throughout the process of deportation to the death camps, any citizens considered too weak to travel were shot in the town square. This could be due to illness, age, or injury. Those left behind after the deportation were sent to the ghetto of [[Tarn\u00f3w Ghetto|Tarn\u00f3w]] or killed.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Jewish cemetery|Kirkut]] cemetery was the site of many executions from the Brzesko Ghetto. \n\nThroughout the lifespan of the ghetto Jews within the ghetto worked to escape. Some of the Jews escaped into the nearby woods where they hid until they could escape or were caught.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Sisters' Story|last=Leiter|first=Robert|date=2008|work=Jewish Exponent|access-date=}}</ref> Other Jews tried to escape by using fake Aryan documents forged for them.<ref name=\":2\" /> Paulina Tider and her family were part of the group that got Aryan papers to escape Brzesko.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn73379|title=Oral history interview with Paulina Tider - Collections Search - United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|website=collections.ushmm.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-05}}</ref> Dov Landau managed to escape with his father  in June 1942.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1916624/holocaust-survivor-dov-landau-gives-first-hand-account|title=Holocaust survivor Dov Landau gives first-hand account of the horrors of war|date=2016-02-27|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Anyone who was caught outside the ghetto boundaries was caught by the [[Blue Police|Polish police]] guarding the ghetto and delivered to the [[Gestapo]].<ref name=\":2\" /> During the deportation, Dr. Jan Brzeski helped some of the Jews who had escaped by keeping them healthy until they could come out of hiding.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIt is estimated 200 Jews from Brzesko survived.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOne [[Righteous Among the Nations]], Helena Skrobotowicz, saved one child of the Brzesko Ghetto. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://righteous.yadvashem.org/|title=The Righteous Among the Nations Database|website=The Righteous Among the Nations Database|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Jewish Council (Judenrat) of Brzesko ==\nThe [[Judenrat]] was formed to meet the demands of the Germans through forced labor.<ref name=\":2\" /> Though the council was made up of Jews who believed they were making a difference, the purpose of the served only German needs. This included taking a census of Brzesko which showed that 3,270 Jews lived in Brzesko on 31 May 1941.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />  The division of the Jewish Council was led by Jakub Hendler who also oversaw the counties of [[Szczurowa]] and [[Borz\u0119cin, Lesser Poland Voivodeship|Borzecin]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAdditional groups within Brzesko included the Central Organization for Orphan Care (CENTOS), Jewish Social Self-Help (JSS), and Committee for the Aid to Refugees and the Poor.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Post war ==\nThe Jewish cemetery still contains the graves of those who died during WWII.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmentarze.gorlice.net.pl/Brzesko/okreg7_cz3.htm#276|title=Robert Koz\u0142owski|website=www.cmentarze.gorlice.net.pl|access-date=2018-05-05}}</ref> In 1947, a monument to remember the mass grave of the 200 Jews who died in Brzesko on 18 June 1942 was built in the Jewish cemetery.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> <ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://sztetl.org.pl/pl/miejscowosci/b/463-brzesko/116-miejsca-martyrologii/44954-cmentarz-zydowski-w-brzesku-miejsce-egzekucji-i-pochowku-ofiar-zaglady-ul-czarnowiejska|title=Cmentarz \u017cydowski w Brzesku - miejsce egzekucji i poch\u00f3wku ofiar Zag\u0142ady (ul. Czarnowiejska) {{!}} Wirtualny Sztetl|website=sztetl.org.pl|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\nA [[commemorative plaque]] is also displayed on a wall of the town library which is located on the previous site of the [[:pl:Synagoga_w_Brzesku|synagogue of Brzesko]].<ref name=\":7\" /><br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:The Holocaust]]\n[[Category:Polish Jews]]\n[[Category:Ghettos in Nazi-occupied Europe]]\n[[Category:Jewish ghettos in Nazi-occupied Poland]]\n", "name_user": "Charc2018", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brzesko_Ghetto"}
